{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":491,"record_hash":"sha256:41db87c982b659d02c0695f15ac8659b3df520d76e718f702d6c9f86a8f62b25","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:44:37.055Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md\n@@\n ## Entry Point\n \n-The first expected entry point is a pull request link.\n-\n-Possible GitHub placement:\n-\n-- PR description link added by GitButler\n-- PR comment posted by GitButler\n-- check-run details link\n-- GitHub app panel, if that becomes available later\n-\n-The simplest first version is probably a PR description or bot comment link.\n-Check-run UI may be nicer later, but it adds product and permission complexity.\n-\n-## On-Demand URL Entry\n-\n-It would be useful if Agent Trail pages can be created on demand from an\n-existing forge URL.\n+The first entry point is on-demand URL replacement from an existing GitHub pull\n+request URL.\n \n Example:\n \n@@\n The backend would parse the forge URL shape, resolve the repository and pull\n request, check whether it has access, then build or load the Agent Trail\n overview for that PR.\n \n+Accept only canonical GitHub pull request route shapes. Strip query strings,\n+hashes, and trailing slashes. Do not accept arbitrary git URLs or fetch remotes\n+derived from unchecked user input.\n+\n For GitHub PRs, the pull request number should map to the `but-agentlog`\n `review` target. For example, PR `13936` should query the review target value\n `13936`, which `but-agentlog` normalizes to the stored key:\n@@\n \n The server can also use the GitHub API to resolve PR metadata, especially the\n-head branch behind the pull request. For the URL above, the lookup flow should\n-be:\n+head branch behind the pull request. The canonical v1 flow is:\n \n ```text\n-parse PR URL -> fetch GitMeta -> query review target gitbutler-review:13936\n+parse PR URL -> GitHub PR lookup -> initialize/refresh repo cache\n+-> fetch refs/meta/main -> but-agentlog lookup -> snapshot page\n ```\n \n The server should fetch public PR metadata from GitHub, resolve the PR head\n branch, and search both useful MVP targets in one pass:\n@@\n Current preference: search both when PR metadata is already available, then rank\n-review-target hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub API lookup fails or is rate\n-limited, the server can still return review-target results from GitMeta alone.\n+review-target hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub PR lookup fails, v1 should\n+fail closed with a retryable error state instead of guessing from GitMeta alone.\n \n Branch fallback is useful but weaker. A branch can be reused, renamed, or shared\n across unrelated work. The UI should show why each session matched and avoid\n treating branch-only matches as proof that the session belongs to the PR.\n+Branch-only matches should be visually separated from review-target matches and\n+raw record drill-down for branch-only matches should require an explicit expand.\n \n Change target lookup is not relevant for the MVP. It can be considered later if\n Agent Trail needs a deeper GitButler-specific view of stacked changes.\n \n-Access can come from:\n-\n-- the repository being public/open source\n-- the user authenticating with GitHub\n-- a GitButler or Forge installation having repository access\n-- a previously published trail snapshot with an allowed share policy\n-\n The first version should focus on public/open-source repositories. Private\n repository access, GitHub OAuth, GitButler workspace access, and explicit share\n links can come later.\n \n-This entry point should still respect the publication boundary. Rewriting a URL\n-should not automatically expose private captured context. It should create a\n-request for an Agent Trail, then show one of:\n+For public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as\n+already published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to\n+private data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable\n+without credentials.\n+\n+This entry point should show one of:\n \n - an existing published trail\n - a newly generated review-safe overview, if access and policy allow it\n-- an authentication prompt\n - a clear \"no trail available\" state\n \n On-demand generation is attractive because it avoids needing every PR to be\n pre-linked by GitButler. It also gives reviewers a memorable gesture: replace\n the forge domain with the Agent Trail domain.\n-\n-Open design questions:\n-\n-- Should generated trails be cached automatically?\n-- Who can publish or persist the generated result?\n-- What should happen when no captured agentlog data exists for the PR?\n-- How should GitHub authentication map to GitMeta/Forge access?\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:44:37.055Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}